  "market_context": "ES daily chart shows a fair value gap below current price with an old low resting directly above it, establishing a bearish draw on liquidity. Price is positioned above the midnight open, and hourly highs rest above as buyside liquidity to be swept before the expected downside delivery.",
  "key_observation": "Using the midnight open as the bias reference, the analyst only sells above the opening price after London session sweeps an hourly high, anticipating displacement down toward the daily fair value gap as drawn liquidity.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Identify the daily draw on liquidity: a daily fair value gap below price with an old low resting above it.",
    "Drop to the hourly chart and mark out the midnight open as the bias reference level.",
    "Locate hourly highs resting above as buyside liquidity to be swept opposite to the drawn liquidity.",
    "Wait for the London session to sweep one of those hourly highs.",
    "Drop to the 5-minute chart and look for displacement down with an order block and fair value gap forming above the opening price.",
    "Take a short entry at or above the opening price with stop on the high of the day, targeting the daily fair value gap.",
    "If the initial entry is missed, look to add or take a continuation entry on further displacement down."
  ],
  "outcome": "Entry would have been triggered with further displacement down; additional continuation entries available if first entry missed. No explicit R-multiple result stated.",
  "lessons": "Bias on the midnight open dictates direction: only sell above open when daily draw is lower. Wait for a London-session hourly liquidity sweep opposite the draw before seeking 5-minute entries at displacement, order block, or fair value gap above the opening price.",
